Scientists have found a way to detect related stars.
Astrophysicists from the University of California in Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of experts will allow us to search among the stars for related ones, i.e. from a single cluster.
The authors published the results of their studies in Nature magazine and are briefly available on the University ' s website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas preceding the formation of the stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine its place of birth and the region of creation of the related stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the models carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, supercomputer experts modelled two interstellar gas streams that together formed a cloud.
This object has been transformed into a cluster of protostars for several million years by its own gravity.
Scientists have added paint marks to the initial gas flows and have found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud has resulted in a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
Astrophysicists believe that their research shows that it is possible to search for chemically related stars and to identify possible regions of origin of such objects.
