Remembering the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that protects union organization as a civil right.
"Where are the unions, there are middle-class jobs," says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chaires the Congress of the Progressive Thrace.
That's why I'm proud to present the Workers Empowerment Act with the symbol of the Civil Rights Movement by John Lewis.
This innovative bill will provide workers with the same legal opportunities to discriminate against the organization of trade unions as other forms of discrimination by stopping the forces of opponents of trade unions
The amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to enable workers facing discrimination in the organization of trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and penalties - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Allison, Lewis, and the co-writers are offering is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that trade unions have suffered in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states throughout the country - Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labour rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans remember when that country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of expression, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArthur and his associates helped the country to adopt a constitution designed to guarantee that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to act collectively is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his associates helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
While recognizing that workers will need to be organized and heard in the new State, the Germans have included an article that explicitly states: "The right to form associations to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to everyone and to every profession or activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will have no legal effect; measures aimed at this purpose will be deemed illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, to be adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "Everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to defend his interests."
For generations, Americans have taken as due the basic premise that labour rights are human rights.
When the country consulted other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and to have the union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is indeed wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago,
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the union movement didn't undermine the nation's power, but it increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions have created a wonderful market for industry and raised a whole nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it should be for us.
Formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and increased protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis are rekindling ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge temporarily block a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge temporarily blocked the enactment of Louisiana's law on Sunday, which his supporters say is likely to close down all five abortion clinics in the state.
According to this measure, which was signed by the Governor of Louisiana, Bobby Ginadle, in June, and was due to enter into force on 1 September, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients at a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge ' s decision meant that doctors could continue to perform legal abortions to date, while continuing to seek such powers.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally, continuing to act to obtain authority," wrote Judge John DeGravells in his decision.
The hearing will be scheduled within one month, at which time the judge will render a more permanent decision on the law.
Lawyers of the right to abortion welcomed this decision, the last in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital powers.
"Today's decision guarantees that the women of Louisiana will be protected from the treacherous law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northap, President and Head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a motion to stop the operation of the law on behalf of three of the five state clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who had not filed a complaint in the case and also applied for admission.
Louisiana is a member of 11 states that have passed such laws, and the courts have recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law that would have closed most of the remaining clinics in that state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Lawyers for the right to abortion, together with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that admission laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not necessary from a medical point of view.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women ' s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who had abortions in Louisiana had the authority to take them to the hospital, reported the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all the other doctors in the state were forced to stop doing this procedure, the doctor, fearing for his safety, would cease doing so, said the team.
Criticizing this decision, Louisiana's officials said that they would not punish abortion doctors while their applications for admission powers were pending.
