The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families had not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools for that time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the border with Gaza, which was greatly spared from Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said, "We will do our utmost to provide you with knowledge and security."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately put an end to hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as the Hamas demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its weapons and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of proximity talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians, three quarters of whom were civilians, and at least 494 children, were killed in the war, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the United Nations.
Israel contests these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; however, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza fighters fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mainly in the south.
Meanwhile, the Israeli army carried out more than 5,000 air attacks and other attacks.
Thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip were damaged and destroyed as a result of Israeli attacks, and an estimated 250,000 people sought refuge in more than 100 schools, which were converted into shelters.
Because tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and fighting continued, education officials postponed the beginning of the school year last week.
"I hope that the school will soon open so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children," said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza's schools.
