Kenya registers civil servants to identify "invisible workers"
Kenya has begun the biometric registration of all government employees in an attempt to remove "invisible workers" from the Government's payroll.
Staff members who are not registered within the next two weeks will no longer be paid in the form of a government application.
The Government suspects that thousands of people continue to receive salaries after leaving the public service.
President Uhuru Keniata has promised to reduce corruption in government structures since he took office in 2013.
An audit earlier this year found that at least $1 million ($70000) per month was lost through payments to "invisible workers" and other financial irregularities.
The Government suspects that salaries continue to flow to bank accounts, even after a person dies or leaves the public service, as reported by BBC reporter Wanyama Chebusiri of the capital, Nairobi.
All civil servants must report to the identification centres within the next two weeks in order to guarantee that their data will be collected through a biometric registration procedure, and must be reported in a government application.
Anyone who fails to do so without a valid reason will be erased from the payroll and reported.
"This procedure will significantly contribute to the rationalization of the public service by determining the actual number of civil servants, and will also be used to clear the payroll at both levels of government - thus putting an end to the problem of "invisible workers," said Ann Waiguru, Secretary of the Cabinet of Ministers for Planning and Organization of Government.
