Genetic abuse is often misdiagnosed
The British reported that she spent many years thinking she'd die after having been misdiagnosed.
Caryn Rogers spent most of her adolescence thinking that she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charco-Marie-Tut's disease, a group of hereditary disorders that caused nerve damage outside her brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that the misdiagnosis is a frequent problem among people with SMTs, because so little is known about this state.
Some 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have a SMT that can cause motor symptoms, such as muscle weakness, insecure walking, and tweaked toes.
The sick may feel numb or pain, and the state does not heal and progress, which means that symptoms increase over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's attack, a state for which the forecast was very bad.
Rogers thought she'd be chained to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and she'd die before she was 30.
The mother of two children, who is now 51, said: "I knew as a child that I could not do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never skate or skateboard with the other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because I was walking and running.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after a few surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten the feet, she looked in the medical file when her doctor left the room, and it said she had an AF.
"I felt guilty because I snuck my nose where I didn't belong, and that's why I didn't tell anyone, but I came home, found information about this condition in the library, and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
