The tax burden on Washington Zone entrepreneurs increases as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and more jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax accounts for companies across the country increased moderately last year, as economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week and a company in the Washington Zone is no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia paid a total of $27.6 billion to the state and local governments in fiscal 2013, 3.8 per cent more than the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden on business at the state and local levels increased by 4.3 per cent last year, to $671 billion, compared with 3.9 per cent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after successive years of decline in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes increased faster, 4.3 per cent than local taxes, 3.9 per cent, according to a study conducted by a professional service firm, Ernst & Young and the State Tax Center, the Tax Policy Unit.
More than half of the tax revenue in the county, 56 per cent, is from business taxes, while 36 per cent of Maryland's tax revenue is from firms.
Virginia, with 28 per cent, generates the lowest tax revenues, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenues is due to a return to the company's previous real estate value, researchers say that it raised real estate taxes by 3.7 per cent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 per cent.
While large states, such as California, New York and Texas, seem to account for a large share of these revenues, the same seems to be happening in the Washington Zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia combined paid $10 billion of state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate does not have any similar effect on the growth of public and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes are barely more than one fifth of the company's tax accounts.
Virginia and District of Columbia pay about half of the state and local tax accounts in the form of real estate taxes.
"What happens in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around D.C., belongs to either the government or a non-profit organization that doesn't pay real estate taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, Executive Director of the Center for State Taxation.
Thus, Maryland has to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully attributed to the re-establishment of the real estate market.
Business revenues also seem to be improving, according to these figures.
Companies in the region declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, most of it in the region.
Although trends are in the same direction, the tax burden on local entrepreneurs does not increase at the same rate in all three locations.
Growth in Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 per cent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 per cent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the 4.1 per cent average.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) equal to 6 per cent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 per cent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 per cent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year revealed that in Virginia taxes are lower for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favourable tax climate for entrepreneurs than in Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its southern neighbour.
North Carolina recently signed a law reducing the corporate rate this year from 6.9 per cent to 6 per cent, just as in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 per cent next year.
If the state continued to meet tax revenue targets in the following year, the law could raise the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to even 3 per cent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington Zone seem to feel better and thus pay more taxes on the state and local level, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneurial taxes paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners - a transitional structure in which most small firms operate - in Columbia, Maryland and Virginia grew by 20 per cent last year to $2.4 billion, at a much higher rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs as a whole.
Researchers say that the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments rising by 6.2 per cent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington Zone may lag behind, as the decline in federal spending affects the labour market in the region.
