The angry expression of the face - the swollen and lowered eyebrows drawn into the thin line of the lips, the bloated nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and it is made by even blind children who have never seen it, notes the leading author of the study, Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have learned that this emotion has emerged for the effective management of disputes during conflict.
The more physical harm one person can cause to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he conveys it to the other by means of anger.
Researchers have also found other hypotheses: physically powerful people are more likely to be angry and to engage in handicraft, consider themselves entitled to impose conditions that are not favourable to others, and prefer violent methods of conflict resolution to be peaceful.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining," scientists have decided that the movement of each of the seven groups of muscles creating an angry face should represent an angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interviewer - thus forcing him to accept its terms as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, researchers modeled a person on a computer where each of the seven elements of an angry face was present or absent and showed them to informants.
Although the lower eyebrows or the forward chin did not individually make the face angry, the more powerful physical participants in the study recognized the human face with such characteristics.
Man's anger, like that of animals, poses a threat: an exaggerated display of his own power, forcing him to accept and submit.
A man inflates nostrils and squeezes his lips for the same purpose as a frog who inflates, or a baboon who shows his fangs.
"The anger is "launched" by the interviewer's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that shows the opposite party the consequences of the refusal as effectively as possible.
But the most striking - that none of the components of the anger face is arbitrary, all of them express the same thing" - noted Anthropologist John Tuby.
The Ministry of Communications has offered 250 million rubles to Crimea.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget in 2014 to the autonomous non-profit organization Teleradio Company Crimea.
This is stated in a draft government decree prepared by the department that Lenta.ru has read.
According to the explanatory note to the project, federal subsidies will be "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment."
In particular, it is intended to upgrade the hardware and studio unit, the video wall, the central hardware and the video server for the money allocated.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of the fibre-optic link (VOLS) and the repair of the power system.
Grants will be provided within the federal budget allocated to the Ministry of Communications.
The State Broadcasting Company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, over 75 per cent of the peninsula has been covered by television and radio.
In 2011, Crimean Teleradio Company was granted a digital television broadcasting licence.
